'''''Deiva Magan''''' ({{lang-en|Divine Son}}) is a 1969 [[Tamil language]] film starring [[Sivaji Ganesan]] in a triple role. Sivaji Ganesan enacted three roles for the second time in his career after ''[[Bale Pandiya (1962 film)|Bale Pandiya]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/fline/fl1816/18161130.htm |title=A doyen among actors |publisher=Hindu.com |date=1928-10-01 |accessdate=2011-06-05 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref> He acted as a father and two sons.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/fr/2002/07/19/stories/2002071900990600.htm |title=Incredible charisma on screen |publisher=The Hindu |date= 2002-07-19|accessdate=2011-06-05 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref> The film has [[Pandari Bai]] and [[Jayalalithaa Jayaram|Jayalalitha]] as the female lead. The film was the first ever Tamil film to be [[List of Indian submissions for Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film|submitted by India in contest for the Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]].<ref>{{cite book|last=R.L|first=Hardgrave|title=Essays in the political sociology of South India|year=1979|publisher=Usha|page=120|accessdate=11 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=India<U+2019>s Oscar drill|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/indias-oscar-drill/265710/2|work=The Indian Express|publisher=www.indianexpress.com|accessdate=4 June 2011}}</ref> The film had a song "Deivamae Deivamae" sung by [[T. M. Soundararajan]] which became very popular.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/fr/2004/12/24/stories/2004122402511500.htm |title=Entertainment / Interview : Encomiums to an evergreen talent |publisher=The Hindu |date=2004-12-24 |accessdate=2011-06-05 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref> Ganesan's performance in this film was well acclaimed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/54310.html |title=Romancing the Romance - I - Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date= |accessdate=2011-06-11}}</ref><ref name="Dmg">{{cite web|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/PDATOI/articleshow/7864345.cms |publisher=The Times of India |title=Vikram to play Krishna! |date=2011-04-05 |accessdate=2011-06-11}}</ref>

==Plot==
The film has Sivaji Ganesan portarying three roles; an in secured father, a timid son and an angst-ridden twin brother.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/fr/2002/07/19/stories/2002071900990600.htm |title=Incredible charisma on screen |publisher=The Hindu |date= 2002-07-19|accessdate=2011-06-08 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref> Sivaji Ganesan, a lawyer with a scarred face gets married to Pandari Bai. The couple lead a happy life and Pandari Bai gives birth to twin brothers, a son with a scarred face (Also Ganesan) like his father and a brother (Also Ganesan). Their father unable to tolerate his eldest son's face leaves him under the custody of another person and tells his wife that the first child is dead. As years pass by, the father becomes a justice and his younger son, a happy-go-lucky college-going timid son falls in love with [[J. Jayalalithaa|Jayalalithaa]]. In the meanwhile, the elder son comes to know about his family and tries to meet his mother and brother but he is asked by his father not to reveal his identity to them. [[M. N. Nambiar]], a man once punished by the father kidnaps the younger son in order to take revenge on him. In the end, the elder son rescues his brother, killing M. N. Nambiar and also gets killed, dying on the lap of his mother (Pandari Bai).

